class TreeNode {
    constructor(val, left=null, right=null) {
        this.val = (val === undefined ? 0 : val);
        this.left = (left === undefined ? null : left);
        this.right = (right === undefined ? null : right);
    }
}

function minSwaps(root) {
    let count = 0;
    let que = [{ node: root, depth: 0 }];

    let levelVals = [];
    let prevDepth = -1;

    while (que.length > 0) {
        const { node, depth } = que.shift();

        if (prevDepth !== depth) {
            levelVals.sort((a, b) => a - b);
            for (let i = 1; i < levelVals.length; ++i) {
                count += Math.abs(levelVals[i] - levelVals[i-1]) - 1;
            }
            prevDepth = depth;
            levelVals = [];
        }
        levelVals.push(node.val);

        if (node.left) que.push({ node: node.left, depth: depth + 1 });
        if (node.right) que.push({ node: node.right, depth: depth + 1 });
    }

    levelVals.sort((a, b) => a - b);
    for (let i = 1; i < levelVals.length; ++i) {
        count += Math.abs(levelVals[i] - levelVals[i-1]) - 1;
    }

    return count;
}
```

    The algorithm uses a breadth-first search to traverse through each level of the binary tree. It keeps track of the current level of nodes by using a queue and the depth of the current node. At each level, we store the node values into a list (called `levelVals`).

Once we have reached a new level or finished traversal, we sort the list of the previous level's node values and calculate the total number of swaps needed to make the previous level sorted in increasing order. Let `a` and `b` be the sorted values of the previous and the next element in that level. The swaps at each step are calculated as `abs(a - b) - 1`, and we update the `count` variable.

After the last level, we perform the same calculation for swaps, and finally return the `count` as the result.

